 > >No David, from the description of the key generation algorithm published
 > >you'll see tha the user's key is entirely determined from the chip's serial
 > >number and two seed numbers.  The seed numbers are the back door.  If they
 > >weren't the back door, random bits from a particle counter or an ultra high
 > >speed unstable flipflop would be used instead.
 >
 > Since the seed numbers are provided by the escrow agencies and aren't
 >recorded, and they are destroyed after each chip programming session, I
 >think not.

 What insures that the folks who bring the chip-programming gadget to the
party aren't recording the numbers that are burned into the chips -- or,
for that matter, simply burning the same secret numbers into any chip while
providing a phony readout to satisfy the escrow agents?
